   "highlightNeurons":[[1,1]]},
  {"type":"label","id":"calc","x":80,"y":440,"text":"z_2 = 0.8(0.8) + 0.6(-0.4) + (-0.2) = 0.20,\\ a_2 = \\tanh(0.20) = 0.20","latex":true}
] }
```

```scene step=4 narration="Hidden neuron 2: z = -0.4·0.8 + 0.9·(-0.4) + 0.3 = -0.38. a = tanh(-0.38) = -0.36. Light red (negative)." code_lines=9-10
{ "primitives": [
  {"type":"nn","x":100,"y":90,"width":600,"height":320,
   "layers":[
     {"size":2,"label":"input","activations":[0.8,-0.4]},
     {"size":3,"label":"hidden","activations":[0.80,0.20,-0.36]},
     {"size":1,"label":"output"}
   ],
   "weights":[[[1.0,-0.5],[0.8,0.6],[-0.4,0.9]],[[0.7,-0.3,0.5]]],
   "highlightEdges":[[0,0,1,2],[0,1,1,2]],
   "highlightNeurons":[[1,2]]},
  {"type":"label","id":"calc","x":80,"y":440,"text":"z_3 = -0.4(0.8) + 0.9(-0.4) + 0.3 = -0.38,\\ a_3 = \\tanh(-0.38) = -0.36","latex":true}
] }
```

```scene step=5 narration="All hidden activations computed. Now flow into the output neuron: combine via W^(2) = (0.7, -0.3, 0.5)." code_lines=12-13
{ "primitives": [
  {"type":"nn","x":100,"y":90,"width":600,"height":320,
   "layers":[
     {"size":2,"label":"input","activations":[0.8,-0.4]},
     {"size":3,"label":"hidden","activations":[0.80,0.20,-0.36]},
     {"size":1,"label":"output"}
   ],
   "weights":[[[1.0,-0.5],[0.8,0.6],[-0.4,0.9]],[[0.7,-0.3,0.5]]],
   "highlightEdges":[[1,0,2,0],[1,1,2,0],[1,2,2,0]],
   "highlightNeurons":[[2,0]]},
  {"type":"label","id":"calc","x":80,"y":440,"text":"z^{(2)} = 0.7(0.80) + (-0.3)(0.20) + 0.5(-0.36) + 0.0 = 0.32","latex":true}
] }
```

```scene step=6 narration="Apply tanh to the output pre-activation. Final prediction: a^(2) = tanh(0.32) = 0.31." code_lines=13
{ "primitives": [
  {"type":"nn","x":100,"y":90,"width":600,"height":320,"label":"Forward pass complete",
   "layers":[
     {"size":2,"label":"input","activations":[0.8,-0.4]},
     {"size":3,"label":"hidden","activations":[0.80,0.20,-0.36]},
     {"size":1,"label":"output","activations":[0.31]}
   ]},
  {"type":"label","id":"out","x":80,"y":440,"text":"\\hat{y} = \\tanh(0.32) = 0.31","latex":true}
] }
```

## Quiz

?? If the hidden layer used the identity function instead of $\tanh$, the network would be mathematically equivalent to what?
>> A single linear layer. Without a nonlinearity, composing two linear transformations $W^{(2)} W^{(1)} x$ is just another linear map — the hidden layer adds no representational power. Nonlinearities (tanh, ReLU, sigmoid) are what let deep networks model complex functions.

?? In this trace we never changed the weights. What would it take to make the network actually *learn*?
>> Backpropagation. Pick a loss function (e.g. $(\hat{y} - y)^2$ for regression). Compute the gradient of the loss with respect to each weight using the chain rule — essentially running a backward pass where each layer passes its error signal to the previous layer. Then apply gradient descent: $w \leftarrow w - \eta \cdot \partial L / \partial w$. Repeat over many input/target pairs.
